1. Code inspection (backend/app/routes/zotero.py, auth_callback,
   lines 149-185): confirmed there is genuinely only ONE db.commit()
   call in the successful path, inside rotate_session (backend/app/
   models/identity.py line 70). The ZoteroConnection insert at line
   170 is followed only by db.flush() (line 174), which pushes the
   INSERT to the DB within the open transaction (visible to
   rotate_session's own subsequent SELECT of session-scoped rows) but
   is not durable — nothing survives a rollback or an uncommitted
   connection close after a flush alone. backend/app/db.py's
   get_session() uses `with Session(get_engine()) as session: yield
   session`; SQLAlchemy's Session context manager closes the session
   on exit (including exceptional exit) without committing, which
   rolls back any not-yet-committed work. This matches the claimed
   fix exactly — confirmed by direct reading, not by trusting the
   PIVOT log's description.

